{"ticker": "SNPS", "company": "SYNOPSYS INC", "weight_sum": 7.68, "etfs": ["ARKQ", "PRNT", "ARKX"], "is_private": false, "query": "($SNPS OR \"Synopsys\") -is:retweet min_faves:10 since:2026-04-28 until:2026-04-29", "n_fetched": 6, "n_kept": 3, "n_dropped": 3, "kept": [{"type": "tweet", "id": "2049039954274087317", "url": "https://x.com/DesFrontierTech/status/2049039954274087317", "twitterUrl": "https://twitter.com/DesFrontierTech/status/2049039954274087317", "text": "$IONQ\n\nMartin Roetteler is VP of Quantum Solutions at IonQ. He showed a Rolls-Royce jet engine.\n\nThe jet engine is a computer model. Engineers break a complex object into millions of tiny connected pieces, simulate how each piece responds to forces, and combine the answers to predict how the whole object behaves. The Rolls-Royce model has 34.9 million points and 870.6 million connections between them.\n\nEngineers use models like this to study how a real jet engine vibrates, deforms, and crashes under stress.\n\nThe model is too large to run on any single computer chip. It has to be distributed across many processors working in parallel. The processors constantly share data with each other. If the work is split badly, they spend more time sharing data than computing. The whole simulation slows down.\n\nIonQ inserted a quantum computer into the workflow. The quantum computer figures out the best way to divide the work among the regular processors. Better division means less wasted time. Less wasted time means faster results. Everything else in the workflow stays the same.\n\nThe Rolls-Royce jet engine ran 15% faster.\n\nA sedan car with 5.9 million points ran 7% faster. The oil well drill ran 15% faster, the impeller 10%. Every industrial model tested cleared 7%.\n\nThese are not toy problems. The drill is an actual oil well drill, not a Bosch consumer drill. Synopsys is the customer. Their workflow runs in production for automotive and aerospace companies.\n\nThe work ran on IonQ Forte, a 36-qubit 